                <note rend="inline" type="source">500. A 4e/108: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-10-05T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 5, 1922—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>236. Your telegram 403, October 2, 4 p.m.</p>
                <p>Until Customs Treaty of February 6 has come into force the Department cannot
                    affirmatively approve alteration of tariff schedules fixed by Treaty of October
                    20, 1920. As indicated in Department’s telegram No. 235 September 27 you may
                    however advise Chinese Government that this Government will interpose no
                    objection to the arrangement suggested in the Chinese Foreign Office note of
                    September 30 pending deposit of ratifications provided this arrangement is
                    accepted by all interested governments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
